  </section>
  <section class="explainer explainer-themes">
    <div class="inside">
      <h2>Customize the Look</h2>
      <p>Choose from a selection of handcrafted, minimalist, responsive themes.</p>
      <div class="theme-thumbs">
        <img class="full-img" src="images/bitbooks-mobile-sizes.png" />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section class="explainer explainer-os">
    <div class="inside">
      <h2>Open source or bust.</h2>

      <p>We've released the static site framework that runs Bitbooks as an open source project called "<a href="https://github.com/bryanbraun/franklin">Franklin</a>." It's like <a href="http://octopress.org/">Octopress</a> for book projects. You should really check it out.</p>

      <a href="https://github.com/bryanbraun/franklin"><img class="franklin-img" src="images/franklin.png"></a>

      <p><small>We are also sharing <a href="https://github.com/bryanbraun/anchorjs">this javascript utility</a>, <a href="https://github.com/bryanbraun/frontend-styleguide">this styleguide template</a>, and <a href="https://github.com/bryanbraun/middleman-navtree">this ruby gem</a>. Yay <a href="http://tom.preston-werner.com/2011/11/22/open-source-everything.html" target="_blank">open source</a>!</small></p>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section class="explainer explainer-0">
    <div class="inside">
      <img class="bb-diff" src="images/bitbooks-diff-sm.png" />
      <h2>Why?</h2>
      <p>We love creative commons books like <a href="http://git-scm.com/book" target="_blank">Scott Chacon's Pro Git</a>, and <a href="http://diveintohtml5.info/" target="_blank">Mark Pilgram's Dive into HTML5</a>. They are well designed. They show up in search results. They are available in various formats and languages. The idea behind Bitbooks is to make it easy for Developers to write and maintain books like these, using Github as a collaborative writing platform.</p>
    </div>
  </section>